🗂️ Part 2 — View Your Hosted Zone:
          
          Step 1 — Navigate to Hosted Zones:
                    In the Route 53 left panel → Click "Hosted zones"
                    You will see your newly created hosted zone:
                    needtoknowec2.com
                    💡 AWS automatically creates a Hosted Zone when you register a domain through Route 53. You do NOT need to create it manually.
          Step 2 — Open the Hosted Zone:
                    Click on needtoknowec2.com to open it
                    You will see 2 default records automatically created:
                    Step 3 — The 2 Auto-Created DNS Records:

                    #	Record Name	Type	Purpose
                    1	needtoknowec2.com	NS	Name Server — tells the internet which AWS name servers are authoritative for your domain
                    2	needtoknowec2.com	SOA	Start of Authority — contains administrative info about the zone (primary NS, admin email, TTL, serial number)
                    What each record means:
                              NS Record (Name Server):
                              ns-123.awsdns-45.com
                              ns-456.awsdns-67.net
                              ns-789.awsdns-89.org
                              ns-012.awsdns-34.co.uk
                    💡 Route 53 assigns 4 name servers automatically. These tell the internet — "AWS manages DNS for this domain."
